<dl id="s17033b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us17" href="#s17033b">Ithaca: </a><a href="../../FF/unbs/s17all.htm#s17033b">sector 33(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> blood dripping walls</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The omens seen by the second-sighted Theoclymenus <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> are those which everywhere bode death and doom. The shroud of mist covering not only the feet and knees, the sign of apporaching but distant death, but reaching to the head as so as to foreshow that death is even at the doors, is familiar to Martin&apos;s book on the Western Isles of Scotland. The <mark>dripping of blood from the walls</mark> is illustrated by the visions of Bergthora, and Njal, on the night of the slaughter of their family. <small> Butcher &amp; Lang, trans. <a name="OHBL3" href="/udra/udex.htm#OHBL3"><cite title="source">The Odyssey Of Homer</cite></a> (1906), 421 (341 note)</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
